text.tspan: and well-being. Most students reported an increase in academic stress due to the lockdown, as
shown in the 10-point Likert scale analysis (Table 7). One student responded that "Usually I'm a
cool and calm-headed person, but I'm losing it now" (Participant 90), signifying extreme levels
of academic stress and pressure without any means of coping with the distressing environment.
Students expressed concerns for a changed biological clock, laziness, lack of productivity, and
hampered daily routines increasing discontentment and anxiety. However, for some students, the
lockdown has resulted in decreased pressure and reduced academic stress. For example, one
respondent said, "This lockdown rather than being stressful, has been relaxing, and therefore I
did not really have to tackle stress at all" (Participant 79). These findings support the researcher's
hypothesis and suggest that while stress levels for most students increased during the COVID-19
lockdown, a few students responded with decreased academic stress and a more comfortable
work schedule.
